WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.920
 (soft piano music)

00:00:02.920 --> 00:00:12.500
 - Hello, I have a confession to make.

00:00:12.500 --> 00:00:14.020
 Perhaps you've taken a class from me

00:00:14.020 --> 00:00:18.200
 where I misled you on what's going on in Python.

00:00:18.200 --> 00:00:23.300
 But first we gotta take a look into the past.

00:00:23.300 --> 00:00:26.180
 The following two slides are from chapter two

00:00:26.180 --> 00:00:30.220
 of my Python for everybody textbook and course

00:00:30.220 --> 00:00:32.460
 that's available all over the place.

00:00:32.460 --> 00:00:35.140
 It's introduced more people to programming

00:00:35.140 --> 00:00:38.500
 in the millions than any other course in the world.

00:00:38.500 --> 00:00:40.460
 These slides are misleading,

00:00:40.460 --> 00:00:44.140
 and at worst, they are 100% wrong.

00:00:44.140 --> 00:00:46.460
 Let's take a look at the slides and see why.

00:00:46.460 --> 00:00:48.980
 Here's a slide.

00:00:48.980 --> 00:00:51.340
 It's like the fifth slide of that class.

00:00:51.340 --> 00:00:53.340
 A variable is a named place in memory

00:00:53.340 --> 00:00:54.940
 where a programmer can store data

00:00:54.940 --> 00:00:58.180
 and then later retrieve it using the name of the variable.

00:00:58.180 --> 00:01:00.140
 Programmers get to choose the names of the variables.

00:01:00.140 --> 00:01:01.820
 They're like labels in memory location,

00:01:01.820 --> 00:01:04.140
 and you can change the contents of a variable

00:01:04.140 --> 00:01:05.520
 in a later statement.

00:01:05.520 --> 00:01:07.920
 So x equals 12, takes a little drawer,

00:01:07.920 --> 00:01:09.980
 labels it x, puts a 12 in there.

00:01:09.980 --> 00:01:14.980
 Y equals 14, puts a 14 in a drawer and labels it y.

00:01:14.980 --> 00:01:18.820
 But then if you change it like x equals 100 later,

00:01:18.820 --> 00:01:23.340
 that replaces the value 12.2 with the value 100.

00:01:24.700 --> 00:01:26.660
 This is what's really happening.

00:01:26.660 --> 00:01:29.340
 A Python variable is a symbolic name

00:01:29.340 --> 00:01:34.180
 that is a pointer or reference to an object.

00:01:34.180 --> 00:01:36.060
 You can kind of see why I didn't explain this

00:01:36.060 --> 00:01:37.420
 in the very beginning.

00:01:37.420 --> 00:01:39.940
 We actually can use the ID function to say,

00:01:39.940 --> 00:01:43.420
 where is this variable pointing to?

00:01:43.420 --> 00:01:46.380
 Now, not all Pythons, this is the CPython,

00:01:46.380 --> 00:01:49.260
 the Python that is written in C.

00:01:49.260 --> 00:01:52.960
 The CPython, we can ask it, where is it?

00:01:52.960 --> 00:01:55.480
 So if we say x equals 42 and then y equals x,

00:01:55.480 --> 00:01:58.500
 you'd think that'd be two locations in memory,

00:01:58.500 --> 00:01:59.740
 but it's not.

00:01:59.740 --> 00:02:02.420
 It's two pointers to one location in memory.

00:02:02.420 --> 00:02:06.060
 And we can figure this out by saying print ID of x,

00:02:06.060 --> 00:02:09.180
 which is like, hey, where would we find x in memory?

00:02:09.180 --> 00:02:10.140
 And it's got a number.

00:02:10.140 --> 00:02:15.140
 And then we say print ID of y, and it's the same place.

00:02:15.140 --> 00:02:20.300
 So we only have one 42, we don't have two 42s,

00:02:20.300 --> 00:02:22.800
 but we have an x pointer and a y pointer

00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:23.700
 that points to it.

00:02:23.700 --> 00:02:26.940
 So for example, we can say, you know,

00:02:26.940 --> 00:02:31.180
 take the object 300, it's an integer.

00:02:31.180 --> 00:02:36.020
 We say x equals 300, the 300 exists somewhere,

00:02:36.020 --> 00:02:38.940
 and x, when we say x equals 300,

00:02:38.940 --> 00:02:41.860
 it points at that object that exists somewhere

00:02:41.860 --> 00:02:44.020
 and it has a location.

00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:47.260
 And then what happens, if we say x equals 2,000,

00:02:47.260 --> 00:02:51.300
 the 2,000 is a different object in a different location,

00:02:51.300 --> 00:02:54.420
 and x then points to the 2,000.

00:02:54.420 --> 00:02:57.860
 The old object integer 300 may still be there,

00:02:57.860 --> 00:02:59.860
 but it's on what we'd call a free list.

00:02:59.860 --> 00:03:01.300
 Some might be on a free list,

00:03:01.300 --> 00:03:05.620
 but the idea is that you're changing the pointer x

00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:08.940
 to point to the integer 2,000 rather than changing

00:03:08.940 --> 00:03:12.240
 the contents of a drawer labeled x to be 2,000.

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:13.740
 Again, if we say y equals x,

00:03:13.740 --> 00:03:17.120
 you'll see that y does not make a copy of 2,000.

00:03:17.120 --> 00:03:20.800
 It simply points to where the same 2,000

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:22.620
 that x is pointing to.

00:03:22.620 --> 00:03:27.340
 So y equals x says, take the address that x points to

00:03:27.340 --> 00:03:30.860
 and put that address in y, okay?

00:03:30.860 --> 00:03:34.940
 Now, if we switch to more complex objects like a list,

00:03:34.940 --> 00:03:37.040
 it makes a little more sense.

00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:39.980
 x equals list says, let's make a list,

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:42.220
 and we can say, print id of x,

00:03:42.220 --> 00:03:44.860
 and that says, this is where it's at.

00:03:44.860 --> 00:03:47.140
 And we can append hello to it.

00:03:47.140 --> 00:03:50.840
 Now, the thing is, that didn't change where x was,

00:03:50.840 --> 00:03:53.220
 but it did change what was in x.

00:03:53.220 --> 00:03:55.780
 So x append hello adds hello to the end of my list,

00:03:55.780 --> 00:03:57.460
 and I can say, where's x?

00:03:57.460 --> 00:04:01.660
 Print id of x, and it's in the same location, okay?

00:04:01.660 --> 00:04:04.940
 Now, if I make a copy, not exactly a copy,

00:04:04.940 --> 00:04:08.900
 when I say y equals x, that makes a new y

00:04:08.900 --> 00:04:11.380
 that points at the same place.

00:04:11.380 --> 00:04:16.380
 And that's why, if we do an x.append world and print y,

00:04:16.740 --> 00:04:19.500
 we see hello world, even though we appended to x,

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:24.500
 and that is because y and x are pointing to the same place.

00:04:24.500 --> 00:04:28.880
 So y equals x is not copying,

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:32.020
 as we might expect in the drawer analogy,

00:04:32.020 --> 00:04:35.340
 it's not copying it, it's just adding a new pointer.

00:04:35.340 --> 00:04:39.580
 Now, sometimes you actually want

00:04:39.580 --> 00:04:41.300
 to make a full copy of something.

00:04:41.300 --> 00:04:45.300
 You got a list, you want an independent list.

00:04:45.300 --> 00:04:47.900
 And so, this is a pattern that we would call

00:04:47.900 --> 00:04:50.780
 copy constructor, there's other ways to describe this.

00:04:50.780 --> 00:04:53.820
 We make a list, x equals list, print id of x,

00:04:53.820 --> 00:04:56.220
 it's at a location, we append hello to it,

00:04:56.220 --> 00:04:58.100
 x is in the same place.

00:04:58.100 --> 00:05:00.380
 Now, instead of saying y equals x,

00:05:00.380 --> 00:05:03.060
 we say y equals list paren x,

00:05:03.060 --> 00:05:05.740
 list is the constructor for lists.

00:05:05.740 --> 00:05:08.820
 And that says, read through the list x,

00:05:08.820 --> 00:05:11.300
 and make full and independent copies

00:05:11.300 --> 00:05:13.660
 of everything in that list, and make a new list,

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:16.820
 and have y point to that, that's what it's saying.

00:05:16.820 --> 00:05:19.940
 So if we say, where is y, print id of y,

00:05:19.940 --> 00:05:22.820
 we see that the x is in one location,

00:05:22.820 --> 00:05:25.900
 and the y is a list that's in another location.

00:05:25.900 --> 00:05:29.800
 And then, if we add world to x, and we print it,

00:05:29.800 --> 00:05:33.440
 we see hello world, but y, because it's an independent copy

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:38.180
 stored at a different location, print y just says hello.

00:05:38.180 --> 00:05:41.400
 Okay, so that is a copy constructor.

00:05:41.400 --> 00:05:44.840
 So if you ask chat GPT, like, what's a Python variable?

00:05:44.840 --> 00:05:49.420
 Chat GPT is wrong, it is bought into the simplification.

00:05:49.420 --> 00:05:51.220
 Now, if you dig in a little deeper,

00:05:51.220 --> 00:05:53.720
 you can say, are you sure it's not a location,

00:05:53.720 --> 00:05:56.060
 but it really a pointer to a location,

00:05:56.060 --> 00:05:58.100
 blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

00:05:58.100 --> 00:06:01.820
 But perhaps it's because so many textbooks like mine

00:06:01.820 --> 00:06:05.300
 start in the beginning with that grand oversimplification.

00:06:05.300 --> 00:06:09.420
 Now, I'm very, very sorry to have misled you

00:06:09.420 --> 00:06:11.500
 back in Python for everybody.

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:15.540
 But the notion of a variable being a drawer is not wrong,

00:06:15.540 --> 00:06:17.860
 it's just wrong in Python.

00:06:17.860 --> 00:06:21.920
 Things like languages like C, or Fortran, or COBOL,

00:06:21.920 --> 00:06:23.980
 they tend to have this drawer model

00:06:23.980 --> 00:06:26.260
 where the variable x is one drawer,

00:06:26.260 --> 00:06:27.820
 and the variable y is another drawer,

00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:29.420
 and they have independent things.

00:06:29.420 --> 00:06:32.720
 When you get around to it, when you learn C,

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:35.780
 and I recommend my C programming for everybody course,

00:06:35.780 --> 00:06:40.700
 www.ccfree.com, in chapters five and six of that,

00:06:40.700 --> 00:06:43.740
 you learn about pointers and data.

00:06:43.740 --> 00:06:48.180
 And the key here is that Python was written in C,

00:06:48.180 --> 00:06:52.860
 in the internal implementation of Python, it's C code.

00:06:52.860 --> 00:06:54.540
 And so the notion of a pointer,

00:06:54.540 --> 00:06:56.480
 and the data that the pointer points to,

00:06:56.480 --> 00:06:58.700
 is completely natural in C,

00:06:58.700 --> 00:07:00.980
 it's just been sort of hidden for us.

00:07:00.980 --> 00:07:04.040
 We can take a look at it using the ID function,

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:06.060
 and get a sense of how variables

00:07:06.060 --> 00:07:08.500
 and assignment statements really work.

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:11.480
 So again, sorry to have misled you.

00:07:11.480 --> 00:07:12.980
 I guess it's better late than never

00:07:12.980 --> 00:07:15.900
 for me to talk to you about the real way

00:07:15.900 --> 00:07:18.340
 that assignment statements work in Python.

00:07:18.340 --> 00:07:19.180
 Cheers.

00:07:19.180 --> 00:07:21.760
 (upbeat music)

